'''Benjamin Hale''' (November 23, 1797 – July 15, 1863) was an American [[educator]] and clergyman in the nineteenth century. He is notable for teaching at [[Dartmouth College]] and becoming the first instructor of the first vocational trade school in America.{{sfn|White|1911|p=45, v.1 ''So was established the first technical school, in any true sense of the word, ever founded in the United States. ... the idea which has since bloomed forth in the technical schools...''}}{{sfn|Bailey|1910|p=581 ''He was the first president of the first agricultural and industrial or technical college in all North America, the Gardiner Lyceum...''}}{{sfn|Hobart|1903|p=45, 46}}{{sfn|Hobart college|1922|p=32 ''Still on such an occasion as this it may be well to recall that Benjamin Hale, a graduate of Bowdoin in the class of 1818 and President of Hobart from 1836 to 1858, himself a classical scholar of unusual attainments, was the founder of technical education in this country, having instituted at Gardiner, Maine, the first American trade school.''}}

== Early life ==
Hale was born in [[Newburyport, Massachusetts]], on November 23, 1797. His parents were Thomas Hale and Alice Little Hale. He was the oldest of ten children in the family. Hale's father was an eighth generation descendant of a Thomas Hale from [[Hertfordshire, England]], who came to Newburyport around 1637.{{sfn|Malone|1932|p=96, vol. viii}}

Hale attended [[Atkinson Academy]] starting in 1813. He entered [[Dartmouth College]] in 1814.{{sfn|Smith|1878|p=276}} For health reasons he had to temporarily drop out and entered instead [[The Governor's Academy|Dummer Academy]] in [[Byfield, Massachusetts]].{{sfn|Smith|1878|p=276}} There he was privately tutored by Rev. Abbott.{{sfn|Smith|1878|p=276}} Hale entered [[Bowdoin College]] at the Sophomore class level in February 1816.{{sfn|Malone|1932|p=96, vol. viii}} He earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from that college in September 1818. {{sfn|Malone|1932|p=96, vol. viii}} Hale first taught a year at [[Thornton Academy]].{{sfn|Malone|1932|p=96, vol. viii}} He was a member of the Theological Seminary at [[Andover, Massachusetts]], in the fall of 1819.{{sfn|Smith|1878|p=276}} Hale became a teacher at Bowdoin College in 1820.{{sfn|Malone|1932|p=96, vol. viii}} He taught [[Natural Philosophy]] and Locke's ''[[An Essay Concerning Human Understanding]]'' to the Junior class.{{sfn|Smith|1878|p=277}} His teachings to the Sophomore class were in advanced mathematics and logic.{{sfn|Smith|1878|p=277}} Hale received a master's degree in September 1821 and delivered a Latin [[valedictory]] [[oration]].{{sfn|Smith|1878|p=277}} While he was a teacher at Bowdoin College Hale pursued theological studies.{{sfn|Smith|1878|p=277}} He became an ordained preacher in 1822 and preached at the [[Congregational Church]] in Andover.{{sfn|Malone|1932|p=96, vol. viii}} 
[[File:Mechanical Principles.jpg|thumb|1827 work by Benjamin Hale]]

== Career ==

In 1822 [[Robert Hallowell Gardiner]] offered Hale a position to become the principal and first main instructor of the first vocational trade school in the United States, a new school in [[Gardiner, Maine]].{{sfn|Smith|1878|p=278}} It was a trade school for the education of farmers and [[agronomists]]. Hale accepted the position and delivered an address on the opening of the [[Gardiner Lyceum]] on January 1, 1823.{{sfn|Smith|1878|p=278}} Hale established this as the first vocational trade school in America through his curriculum.{{sfn|Hobart|1903|p=45, 46}}<ref name=EngineeringEducation>{{cite journal |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |year= |title= The First Technical School |journal= Bulletin of the Society for the Promotion of Engineering Education |volume= 4 |issue= 1-7 |pages= 4|publisher= Bulletin of the Society for the Promotion of Engineering Education|doi= |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=5AkCAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA2-PA4|accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=IndustrialArts>{{cite journal |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |year= 1950 |title= Industrial arts & vocational education
 |journal= |volume= 39 |issue= |pages= 142 |publisher= |doi= |url= https://books.google.com/books?ei=HPzmUbW4OeeqywHVvYGABA&id=HVPlAAAAMAAJ&dq=first+trade+technical+vocational+school++%22Benjamin+Hale%22&q=first+%22Benjamin+Hale%22 |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=Sibley>{{cite journal |last1= White |first1= Andrew Dickson |last2= |first2= |year= 1918 |title= The beginnings of Sibley College at Cornel |journal= Sibley Journal of Engineering |volume= 33 |issue= |pages= 57 |publisher= Cornell University |doi= |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=hz5LAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA57&lpg=PA57|accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref> He had twenty students at the beginning.{{sfn|Malone|1932|p=96, vol. viii}} He organized courses into agricultural chemistry, mathematics, natural philosophy, navigation, surveying, and architecture (using his book "Mechanical Principles of Carpentry").{{sfn|Smith|1878|p=278}} Hale also had various courses in [[husbandry]] in the winter months.{{sfn|Malone|1932|p=96, vol. viii}}

Hale became professor of chemistry at Dartmouth College in 1827.{{sfn|Thomas|2010|p=111}} He was for many years an instructor in the Philosophy of Natural History which he taught to the Senior class.{{sfn|Smith|1878|p=278}} Hale was at Dartmouth College from 1827 through 1835.{{sfn|Thomas|2010|p=111}} He was president of Geneva College (later [[Hobart and William Smith Colleges]]) from 1836 to 1858.{{sfn|Barnhart|1954|p=1886}} Hale experimented with student government.{{sfn|Malone|1932|p=96, vol. viii}} He started preaching in 1828 and preached often at the Episcopal Church in [[Dartmouth, Massachusetts]].{{sfn|Malone|1932|p=96, vol. viii}}

== Family ==
Hale married Mary Caroline King on April 9, 1823.<ref name=King>{{cite web |url= http://www.brazoriaroots.com/p7032.htm |title= Munson, Underwood, Horn, Fairfield and Allied Families |last1= Cooper |first1= Laura M.|last2= |first2= |date=  20 May 2009 |website= John Cardinal's Second Site v3.0.0 |publisher=Munson, Underwood, Horn, Fairfield and Allied Families |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref>

Their children were
:Caroline Olive Hale b. 16 Aug 1826, d. 9 Feb 1837
:Benjamin Hale b. 31 Oct 1827
:Mary King Hale b. 3 Apr 1830, d. 28 Dec 1838
:Sarah Elizabeth Hale b. 3 Jul 1832
:Thomas Hale b. 11 Jul 1834
:Cyrus King Hale b. 17 Mar 1838, d. 5 Jun 1874
:Dr. Josiah Little Hale b. 1 Apr 1841<ref name=King/>

== Personality ==
Hale as a youth was known to have the characteristics of a quiet friendly pleasant child and being a studious boy fond of books.{{sfn|Smith|1878|p=276}}

[[Rufus Anderson]], Secretary of the American Board of Commissioners of Foreign Missions, Hale’s one time classmate and roommate writes that their lifetime friendship was founded in similar interests. Anderson says Hale had nearly equal knowledge in all branches of study. He continues in Hale’s description of Mathematics, Languages, and Music to be quick and accurate. Anderson says Hale was sociable and willing to strike up a conversation with anyone at any time. Anderson describes Hale as quite religious.{{sfn|Smith|1878|p=277}}

== Death and legacy ==
Hale died July 15, 1863.<ref name=Ben/> The various courses in [[husbandry]] in the winter he established at the Gardiner Lyceum was followed later by the majority of the agricultural colleges in the United States.{{sfn|Malone|1932|p=96, vol. viii}} Hale conceived the idea of vocational trade schools now seen throughout the United States and the world by his outline of a planned set of technical courses designed for the practical application of science and mathematics to a specific trade.{{sfn|White|1911|p=45, v.1 ''So was established the first technical school, in any true sense of the word, ever founded in the United States. ... the idea which has since bloomed forth in the technical schools...''}}{{sfn|Hobart|1903|p=45, 46}}{{sfn|Bailey|1910|p=581}}

