arry] Cohen: the actor and environmental activist Shailene Woodley (who was actually arrested protesting the pipeline), Native American activist Deborah Parker, and Jane Kleeb, incoming chair of the Nebraska Democratic Party.}}</ref> and the [[National Indigenous Women's Resource Center]].<ref name="ParkerNIWRC">{{Cite web|url=https://www.niwrc.org/content/deborah-parker|title=Deborah Parker|publisher=[[National Indigenous Women's Resource Center]]|archive-url=https://archive.is/20180603054341/http://www.niwrc.org/content/deborah-parker|archive-date=June 3, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=June 3, 2018|quote=Deborah Parker, Tsi-Cy-Altsa (Tulalip/Yaqui), was elected to the Tulalip Tribes Board of Directors in 2012. As a board member, Deborah brings to Tulalip leadership nearly two decades of experience as a policy analyst, program developer, communications specialist, and committed cultural advocate and volunteer in the tribal and surrounding communities.&nbsp;[...] Deborah lives in Tulalip with her husband Myron Dewey (Paiute/Shoshone) and their five children.}}</ref> She is also a co-founder of [[Indigenous Women Rise]].<ref name="CofounderIWR">{{Cite web|url=https://corvallischangemakers.com/deborah-parker/|title=Deborah Parker: We Are The Changemakers Panelist Bio|publisher=Corvallis Changemakers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617001542/https://corvallischangemakers.com/deborah-parker/|archive-date=June 17, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=June 16, 2018|quote=Most recently, Deborah Parker was named to the Democratic National Convention's Platform Committee. She is a trustee for the Smithsonian's National Museum of the American Indian, Vice Chairwoman for the National Our Revolution Organization, Board of Trustee for the National Indigenous Women's Resource Center and Co-Founder for Indigenous Women Rise.}}</ref><ref name="IG2017TC">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chirpe.com/EventSessions.aspx?EVENTID=4158&SESSIONID=1096&DISPLAYMODE=2|title=Indigenous Women Rise (Room 24 B)|date=April 11, 2017|website=ChirpE|department=Legislative / Policy, Women in Tribal Gaming|publisher=Indian Gaming 2017 Tradeshow and Conference|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617004558/https://www.chirpe.com/EventSessions.aspx?EVENTID=4158&SESSIONID=1096&DISPLAYMODE=2|archive-date=June 17, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref>

During the [[Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act of 2013]], Parker successfully campaigned both for the reauthorization and for the inclusion of provisions which gave [[tribal court]]s jurisdiction over [[violent crime]]s against women and families involving non–Native Americans on tribal lands.<ref name="ProudDay">{{Cite news|last=Capriccioso|first=Rob|author-link=Rob Capriccioso|date=February 28, 2013|title=A Proud Day for Tribal Advocates of the Violence Against Women Act|url=https://indiancountrymedianetwork.com/news/politics/a-proud-day-for-tribal-advocates-of-the-violence-against-women-act/|dead-url=yes|department=News (Politics)|work=Indian Country Today|publisher=National Congress of American Indians|issn=1066-5501|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603071756/https://indiancountrymedianetwork.com/news/politics/a-proud-day-for-tribal-advocates-of-the-violence-against-women-act/|archive-date=June 3, 2018|access-date=June 3, 2018|quote=The Violence Against Women Act (VAWA) reauthorization passed the U.S. House on February 28 by a vote of 286 to 138. In a major victory for Indian country, it mirrored the already passed U.S. Senate provisions that allow tribal courts to prosecute non-Indians who commit violence against women and families on Indian lands.&nbsp;[...] The Senate agreed with [Deborah] Parker's position this year on February 12, and the higher chamber last Congress also voted in the affirmative on the tribal provisions, but this was the first time that the House had taken such action.&nbsp;[...] 'The hard work of Deborah Parker and all tribal advocates is a big win for all of us,' [Pamela] Stearns said, adding that she looks forward to continuing the fight with them on behalf of Alaska Native women[.]}}</ref><ref name="RayOfHope">{{Cite news|last=Wang|first=Hansi Lo|date=February 20, 2014|title=For Abused Native American Women, New Law Provides A 'Ray Of Hope'|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/codeswitch/2014/02/20/280189261/for-abused-native-american-women-new-law-provides-a-ray-of-hope|dead-url=no|department=Code Switch|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603061351/https://www.npr.org/sections/codeswitch/2014/02/20/280189261/for-abused-native-american-women-new-law-provides-a-ray-of-hope|archive-date=June 3, 2018|access-date=June 3, 2018|quote=Deborah Parker serves as the Tulalip Tribes' vice chair. For three years, she flew back and forth between Washington state and Washington, D.C., giving speeches and knocking on doors—an experience that she says felt like 'going to war.'&nbsp;[...] It's an alarming statistic that Parker knows all too well from growing up on the reservation.}}</ref><ref name="ProsecutingAJA">{{Cite news|last=Monnet|first=Jenni|date=February 22, 2014|title=Prosecuting non–Native Americans|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2014/2/22/prosecuting-non-nativeamericans.html|dead-url=no|department=U.S.|work=[[Al Jazeera America]]|publisher=[[Al Jazeera Media Network]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180610131552/http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2014/2/22/prosecuting-non-nativeamericans.html|archive-date=June 10, 2018|access-date=June 10, 2018|quote=Raised on the reservation, an early victim of abuse herself, she [Deborah Parker] said listening to the often-daily survival stories of other tribal members led to a moment of awareness.&nbsp;[...] After meeting certain requirements, the Tulalip, along with the Confederated Tribes of the Umatilla Indian Reservation in Oregon and the Pascua Yaqui Tribe of Arizona, now have the judicial authority to try non-Indians for certain domestic violence-related cases under a pilot program of the Violence Against Women Act (VAWA). Congress passed its reauthorization last year, and by March 2015, the tribal provision will take effect for all U.S. tribes. Last year, Parker said she lobbied members of Congress about the measure until her "toes bled." And she said she advocated so frequently on Capitol Hill—500 days to be exact—that even President Barack Obama got to know her by her Indian name.}}</ref> She also served in the [[2016 Democratic National Convention]] as one of the platform committee members representing [[Bernie Sanders]],<ref name="ParkerDNPC">{{Cite news|last=Trahant|first=Mark|author-link=Mark Trahant|date=May 27, 2016|title=Deborah Parker Named to Democrat's Platform Committee|url=https://indiancountrymedianetwork.com/news/politics/deborah-parker-named-to-democrats-platform-committee/|dead-url=yes|department=News (Politics)|work=Indian Country Today|publisher=National Congress of American Indians|issn=1066-5501|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603062311/https://indiancountrymedianetwork.com/news/politics/deborah-parker-named-to-democrats-platform-committee/|archive-date=June 3, 2018|access-date=June 3, 2018}}</ref><ref name="ProgressiveMajority">{{Cite news|last=Nichols|first=John|author-link=John Nichols (journalist)|date=May 24, 2016|title=The Democratic Platform Committee Now Has a Progressive Majority. Thanks, Bernie Sanders.|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/sanders-picks-and-allies-could-write-a-boldly-progressive-platform/|dead-url=no|department=Democrats|work=The Nation|publisher=[[Katrina vanden Heuvel]]|issn=0027-8378|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603063131/https://www.thenation.com/article/sanders-picks-and-allies-could-write-a-boldly-progressive-platform/|archive-date=June 3, 2018|access-date=June 3, 2018|quote=<!--Markup in original; external links omitted as unnecessary.-->The Sanders selections are all noted progressives: Congressional Progressive Caucus co-chair Keith Ellison, academic and activist Cornel West (the author of the groundbreaking 1994 book ''Race Matters'' and a leading member of Democratic Socialists of America), Native American activist and former Tulalip Tribes Vice Chair Deborah Parker (a key advocate for reauthorization of the Violence Against Women Act), and Arab-American Institute President James Zogby (a veteran of many conventions who was an adviser to the campaigns of the Rev. Jesse Jackson, Vice President Al Gore and President Obama).}}</ref> where she "helped to ensure that Native policy initiatives were ultimately rolled into the party's larger platform."<ref name="SearchForAnswers">{{Cite news|last=Capriccioso|first=Rob|author-link=Rob Capriccioso|date=May 18, 2018|orig-year=Edited; originally published May 12, 2017|title=In Trump Era, Native Democrats Desperately Search for Answers|url=https://newsmaven.io/indiancountrytoday/archive/in-trump-era-native-democrats-desperately-search-for-answers-XV01tzEIhk2BW1a6yePYUw/|dead-url=no|department=Archive|work=[[Indian Country Today]]|publisher=[[National Congress of American Indians]]|issn=1066-5501|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614052014/https://newsmaven.io/indiancountrytoday/archive/in-trump-era-native-democrats-desperately-search-for-answers-XV01tzEIhk2BW1a6yePYUw/|archive-date=June 14, 2018|access-date=June 14, 2018|quote=<!--Original links omitted.-->Then last summer, Sanders chose Deborah Parker, former vice chair of the Tulalip Tribes, to serve on the Democratic Platform Committee. Both she and Jodi Gillette-Archambault, Obama's former White House Advisor on Indian Affairs of the Standing Rock Sioux Tribe, helped to ensure that Native policy initiatives were ultimately rolled into the party's larger platform.}}</ref>

==Biography==
Deborah Parker is a member of the [[Tulalip Tribes of Washington]] and is of Tulalip, [[Lummi]],<ref name="WisdomOfTheCedars">{{Cite speech|last=Parker|first=Deborah|title=Wisdom of the Cedars|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P1s3c4lpKzI|access-date=June 17, 2018|type=Video|time=1:43–2:02, 2:15–2:20, and 13:33–13:52|time-caption=Events occur at|location=Orcas Island|department=TEDxOrcasIsland|publisher=[[TEDx Talks]]|publication-date=June 16, 2016|via=[[YouTube]]}}{{flowlist|<!---{{Flowlist}} used to indicate markup, used instead of {{bulleted list}} due to formatting issue with latter. Quote elements used for [[semantic HTML]] markup consistent with |quote= parameter in CS1 templates.-->
* [2:15–2:20]&nbsp;<q>My name goes seven generations back to my grandmother, my [unintelligible] grandmother.</q>
* [13:33–13:52]&nbsp;<q>And I said 'I'm a Coast Salish person—my grandfather comes from Lummi Nation, from the islands from East Saanich, from Cowichan; my grandmother comes from the [unintelligible], from the Snohomish River—and I have no idea what you're talking about.'&nbsp;</q>}}</ref> [[Yaqui]], and [[Apache]] descent;<ref name="EnduringSpiritAwardNAN">{{Cite news|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=<!--No date.-->|title=2010 Enduring Spirit Award Honors Native Women|url=http://goia.wa.gov/Calendar/September/EnduringSpiritYearInReview.pdf|dead-url=yes|format=PDF|department=7th Annual Native Women's Leadership Forum & Enduring Spirit Honoring Luncheon|publisher=[[Native Action Network]]|page=4|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222210041/http://goia.wa.gov/Calendar/September/EnduringSpiritYearInReview.pdf|archive-date=December 22, 2016|access-date=June 13, 2018|via=Washington Governor's Office of Indian Affairs|quote=She [Deborah Parker] carries her great grandmothers Indian name 'tsi-cy-altsa' and is an enrolled member of the Tulalip Tribes and is also of Yaqui/Apache descent.&nbsp;[...] In 2006, Deborah worked with a team of Native colleagues to form Native Vote Washington as a 501 (c)(4) organization to encourage Indian participation in the political process.}}</ref> her native name, Tsi-Cy-Altsa,{{efn|name="NativeNameVar"}} extends back multiple generations on her mother's side.<!--All sources, including Parker herself, claim seven with the exception of Parker once stating four generations during a speech. Maybe she misspoke?--><ref name="NativeName" /><ref name="WisdomOfTheCedars" /> Her grandfather, who was of [[Lummi]] heritage, was from [[Cowichan Bay]]; her grandmother was from the [[Snohomish River]] area.<ref name="WisdomOfTheCedars" /><ref name="LoveAtTheCrossroads">{{Cite speech|last=Parker|first=Deborah|date=October 28, 2017|title=Deborah Parker: Love at the Crossroads – Climate and Social Justice|event=2nd Annual Faith and Action Climate Team Conference|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MalZJcypyZE|access-date=July 18, 2018|type=Video|time=0:25–0:38 and 1:36–1:53|time-caption=Events occur at|location=Seattle, Washington|publisher=[[Ed Mays]]<!--Producer for Pirate TV Seattle who recorded this video.-->|publication-date=October 30, 2017|via=[[YouTube]]}}{{flowlist|<!---{{Flowlist}} used to indicate markup, used instead of {{bulleted list}} due to formatting issue with latter. Quote elements used for [[semantic HTML]] markup consistent with |quote= parameter in CS1 templates.-->
* [0:25–0:38]&nbsp;<q>My indigenous name, the name I carry from my grandmother, she was a Snohomish me—&nbsp;well, not a member, she was just Snohomish; there's no membership.</q>
* [1:36–1:53]&nbsp;<q>I was honored to be vice-chair of our tribe [the Tulalip Tribes of Washington], honored to be a mother of three beautiful tribal children, and the daughter of&nbsp;[...] a member of the Tulalip Tribes and my mother is a Yaqui–Apache from the south.</q>}}</ref> Born in 1970<!--Birth month and day suppressed as precautionary per [[MOS:DOB]].--><ref name="Parker1970" /><ref name="Parker43" /> as the daughter of a Tulalip father and Yaqui–Apache mother,<ref name="LoveAtTheCrossroads" /> she grew up on the reservation, where she became intimately familiar with many of the problems facing the Native American community that she later sought to address.<ref name="RayOfHope" /><ref name="ProsecutingAJA" /> In 1999,<ref name="ViewpointsUW">{{Cite magazine|last=Spadafora|first=Mary Jean|editor-last=Marmor|editor-first=Jon|title=Parker named National Indian Parent of the Year|url=https://issuu.com/uwalumni/docs/viewpoints_2012spring|dead-url=no|department=360° View|magazine=Viewpoints|location=University of Washington|publisher=Paul Rucker|publication-date=April 6, 2012|volume=9|issue=1 (Spring 2012)|page=[https://e.issuu.com/issuu-reader3-embed-files/1566/iframe-embed.html?u=uwalumni&d=viewpoints_2012spring&p=10 10]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611185329/https://issuu.com/uwalumni/docs/viewpoints_2012spring|archive-date=June 11, 2018|access-date=June 11, 2018|via=[[issuu]]|quote=Deborah Parker, '99, received the National Indian Education Association's 2011 Parent of the Year Award for her work representing the Tulalip community and for fighting racism in the Marysville School District.&nbsp;[...] Parker, who currently serves as a trustee on the UW Friends of the Educational Opportunity Program Board, is a Tulalip Tribe Legislative Policy Analyst.}}</ref> she graduated from the [[University of Washington]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in American [[ethnic studies]] and [[sociology]].<ref name="ViewpointsUW" /><ref name="CoCprofile">{{Cite web|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/champions/civic-hacking-and-open-government/deborah-parker|title=Deborah Parker|department=[[Champions of Change]] (Civic Hacking and Open Government)|website=[[Whitehouse.gov|The White House of President Barack Obama]]|publisher=[[U.S. Federal Government]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603071846/https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/champions/civic-hacking-and-open-government/deborah-parker|archive-date=June 3, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=June 3, 2018|via=[[National Archives and Records Administration]]}}</ref> Since graduating, Parker has been involved in numerous groups and organizations.<ref name="ThereToHelp">{{Cite news|last=Sheets|first=Bill|date=January 25, 2012|title=If there's a need, she's likely been there to help|url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/if-theres-a-need-shes-likely-been-there-to-help/|dead-url=no|department=Local News|work=[[The Herald (Everett)|The Daily Herald]]|location=Tulalip|publisher=Josh O'Connor|issn=2332-0079|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611193447/https://www.heraldnet.com/news/if-theres-a-need-shes-likely-been-there-to-help/|archive-date=June 11, 2018|access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref>

Prior to working for the [[Tulalip Tribes]], Parker served as the director of the residential healing school of the [[Tsleil-Waututh First Nation]] and participated in the Treaty Taskforce Office of the [[Lummi Nation]], wherein she was mentored by indigenous leaders such as [[Billy Frank Jr.]], [[Joe DeLaCruz]], [[Henry Cagey]], and [[Jewell James]].<ref name="CoCprofile" /> Later, she developed two programs for the Tulalip Tribes: Young Mothers, a culturally relevant initiative for [[teen mother]]s; and the Tribal Tobacco Program, which promoted responsible tobacco use among tribal members while acknowledging tobacco's sacred role among [[indigenous peoples in the United States]].<ref name="CoCprofile" /> From 2005 to 2012,<ref name="PipestemProfile">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pipestemlaw.com/attorney/deborah-parker/|title=Deborah Parker|publisher=[[Pipestem Law]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180610091205/http://www.pipestemlaw.com/attorney/deborah-parker/|archive-date=June 10, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=June 10, 2018|quote=Deborah Parker (Senior Strategist) is the former Vice-Chairwoman of the Tulalip Tribes Board of Directors and a nationally-recognized advocate and activist for the rights of Native women. She served as a Legislative Policy Analyst in the Office of Governmental Affairs from 2005–12 for the Tulalip Tribes.}}</ref> Parker served as the Legislative Policy Analyst in the Office of Governmental Affairs for the Tulalip Tribes;<ref name="CoCprofile" /><ref name="PipestemProfile" /> and, in March 2012,<ref name="TulalipLeaderSpeaks" /><ref name="StoriesOfPain">{{Cite news|last=Turner|first=Jan|date=July 24, 2012|title=Stories of Pain and Perseverance: Rape on the Reservation|url=http://womenetics.com/Security-Stability/stories-of-pain-and-perseverance-rape-on-the-reservation|dead-url=yes|department=Our World Today (Security & Stability)|work=[[Womenetics]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130830211146/http://www.womenetics.com/Security-Stability/stories-of-pain-and-perseverance-rape-on-the-reservation|archive-date=August 30, 2013|access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref> she began serving as vice-chairwoman of the Tulalip Tribes,<ref name="TulalipLeaderSpeaks" /><ref name="Lane2018">{{Cite journal|last=Lane|first=Temryss MacLean|title=The frontline of refusal: indigenous women warriors of standing rock|journal=[[International Journal of Qualitative Studies in Education]]|publisher=[[Routledge]]|publication-date=January 15, 2018|volume=31|issue=3|pages=209–211|doi=10.1080/09518398.2017.1401151|eissn=1366-5898|issn=0951-8398}}</ref>{{rp|209|quote=In 2012, two days into her role as the Vice Chairwoman of Tulalip Tribes, Deborah Parker delivered a powerfully vulnerable testimony to the Senate in support of the VAWA, urging Congress to uphold Treaty agreements and honor the US Constitution (Senator Patty Murray, 2012).}} becoming its only woman board member and its youngest member.<ref name="TulalipLeaderSpeaks" /> After serving three terms as vice-chair, she decided to not seek re-election in 2015 to focus more on her family and activism.<ref name="FormerChair" /><ref name="ParkerInterviewTYT">{{Cite interview|last=Parker|first=Deborah|interviewer=[[John Iadarola]]|title=Deborah Parker Interview At 2016 Democratic National Convention|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Uv94w9QyWA|type=Video|department=TYT Interviews|work=[[The Young Turks]]|date=August 1, 2016|access-date=June 5, 2018|time=0:29–0:36, 1:34–2:02, 2:43–3:07, 5:27–6:12, 9:30–9:39, and 10:51–11:46|time-caption=Events occur at|via=[[YouTube]]}}
{{flowlist|<!---{{Flowlist}} used to indicate markup, used instead of {{bulleted list}} due to formatting issue with latter. Quote elements used for [[semantic HTML]] markup consistent with |quote= parameter in CS1 templates.-->
* [0:29–0:36]&nbsp;<q>About a year ago, I decided to not seek re-election and actually spend more time with my family.</q>
* [1:34–2:02]&nbsp;<q>Well, I was contacted by Debbie Wasserman Schultz from the DNC and when she called me on a Sunday afternoon to say, 'Would you be willing to sit on the platform?' my mind said 'no, thank you' but I actually said 'yes', not knowing the full process. I just thought, 'wow', that this is our opportunity and my opportunity as a Native American woman to—and as a climate activist and I work on Violence Against Women Act issues—&nbsp;[...]</q>
* [2:43–3:07]&nbsp;<q>Personally, I was hoping to achieve, to advance some of the causes that I {{em|have}}<!--Emphasis in original.--> been working on, which is Native American sovereignty, climate justice, to increase—as I was saying—protections for women, income inequality. Those are things that were so important to me and those were the very issues Bernie Sanders was reporting in.</q>
* [5:27–6:12]&nbsp;<q>It's [nationwide legal restrictions on guns for those charged with domestic violence] a necessity; if you truly care about women and the safety of women, then we need to take direct action.&nbsp;[...] and if you're truly committed to protecting women, then let's put legislation forward that protects women and gun safety and legislation that doesn't allow perpetrators and abusers to have guns, which is a huge killer of women.</q>
* [9:30–9:39]&nbsp;<q>It's [Donald Trump referring to Elizabeth Warren as 'Pocahontas'] very insulting to be called something that I'm not—I'm not 'Pocahontas', I'm not from her nation—so I mean it's very deep for us, so it's actually insulting.</q>
* [10:51–11:46]&nbsp;<q>He [Donald Trump] already has a record with the tribal nations that is very seriously flawed.&nbsp;[...] he did try to engage in business with our sovereign nations and he tried to shortcut a lot of the policies and procedures. You can go online and see the testimonies that he took to Congress that really ridiculed and just really hurt our idea—the fact that we have sovereignty, the fact that our constitutionality and our treaties are what protects us. It's part of the Constitution and he wanted to ignore that. You don't ignore that.</q>}}</ref>

While serving the Tulalip Tribes, Parker continued to involve herself in improving education and political engagement among Native Americans in [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. In January 2005, she was elected as the treasurer for Choice & Consequence,<ref>{{Cite news|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=January 5, 2005|title=Nonprofits|url=https://www.heraldbusinessjournal.com/archive/jan05/people-jan05.htm|dead-url=no|department=People Watching|work=Snohomish County Business Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614033111/https://www.heraldbusinessjournal.com/archive/jan05/people-jan05.htm|archive-date=June 14, 2018|access-date=June 14, 2018|via=''[[The Herald Business Journal]]''|quote=<!--Boldfacing in original.-->'''Deborah Parker''' has been elected treasurer and '''Tim Blair''' has been elected vice president of the nonprofit group Choice & Consequence.}}</ref> a [[501(c)(3)]] nonprofit organization that promotes healthy practices among Washington youth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://candc.robinewarren.com/about_organlady.html|title=Choice & Consequence: The Organ Lady Story|department=About|publisher=Choice & Consequence|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612025011/http://candc.robinewarren.com/about_organlady.html|archive-date=June 12, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=June 12, 2018|quote=<!--Fixed formatting and removed trademark symbol from original.-->Our Mission: The Choice & Consequence mission is to educate youth about the consequences of their health behaviors. We show the benefits of choosing wisely using real human organs and empower audiences of all ages to make positive health choices.&nbsp;[...] The Board of Directors set CC up as a nonprofit 501(c)(3) charity in Washington State. On January 1, 2004, Providence Everett Medical Center donated their organ program, 'The Real Inside Story' to Choice & Consequence.}}</ref> She later was promoted to its board of directors as the president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://candc.robinewarren.com/about_board.html|title=Choice & Consequence: Board of Directors|department=About|publisher=Choice & Consequence|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611232326/http://candc.robinewarren.com/about_board.html|archive-date=June 12, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref> In 2006, she participated in the development of Native Vote Washington, a [[501(c)(4)]] organization that sought to encourage greater political participation among Native Americans.<ref name="EnduringSpiritAwardNAN" /> In 2007, Parker starred as Aunt Fran<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://education.wsu.edu/documents/2015/08/shadow-of-the-salmon.pdf/|format=PDF|title=Shadow of the Salmon: Resource Guide|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=<!--None listed.-->|publisher=<!--No specific publisher listed.-->|page=i|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723052949/https://education.wsu.edu/documents/2015/08/shadow-of-the-salmon.pdf/|archive-date=July 23, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=July 23, 2018|via=[[Washington State University]]|quote=[Image caption:] Billy Frank Jr., respected Nisqually elder and longtime Chairman of the Northwest Indian Fisheries Commission, sits among other Shadow of the Salmon cast members. From left: Noah Hunt (Cody), Gene Tagaban (Uncle Ray), Deborah Parker (Aunt Fran) and Roberta Sam (Shawnee).}}</ref> in ''[[Shadow of the Salmon]]'', a [[docudrama]] about the significance of salmon among the [[Northwest Native]] peoples<ref>{{Cite news|last=Walker|first=Richard|date=December 31, 2007|title=News from the Pacific Northwest|url=https://newsmaven.io/indiancountrytoday/news/news-from-the-pacific-northwest-29/|dead-url=no|department=News|work=[[Indian Country Today]]|location=Suquamish, Washington|publisher=[[National Congress of American Indians]]|issn=1066-5501|archive-url=https://newsmaven.io/indiancountrytoday/news/news-from-the-pacific-northwest-29/|archive-date=July 23, 2018|access-date=July 23, 2018|quote=The film premiered Nov. 19 at the Suquamish Clearwater Casino Resort and stars Gene Tagaban, ('The Business of Fancydancing') Tlingit, and Debra&nbsp;[''[[sic]]''] Parker, Tulalip.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://salmondefense.org/projects/educate/shadow-of-the-salmon/|title=Shadow Of The Salmon|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=2007|publisher=[[Salmon Defense]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723051147/https://salmondefense.org/projects/educate/shadow-of-the-salmon/|archive-date=July 23, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref> that was nominated for multiple awards.<ref>{{Cite press release|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=April 13, 2009|title=Locally Produced Film, 'Shadow of the Salmon,' Nominated for Three Regional Emmys|url=https://www.threesixtyproductions.com/news/news_asst/sos_pr_0409.pdf|format=PDF|dead-url=no|type=Press release|department=News|publisher=[[Three Sixty Productions]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723051526/https://www.threesixtyproductions.com/news/news_asst/sos_pr_0409.pdf|archive-date=July 23, 2018|access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref> Later, in September 2010,<ref name="E-NewsUW">{{Cite newsletter|date=September 2010|title=New FEOP Board Members Elected|url=https://www.washington.edu/alumni/partnerships/omad/201009/feop.html|dead-url=no|department=Around Campus|magazine=E-News|type=Newsletter|location=[[University of Washington]]|publisher=Office of Minority Affairs & Diversity|archive-url=https://archive.is/20180611193942/https://www.washington.edu/alumni/partnerships/omad/201009/feop.html#selection-75.183-75.214|archive-date=June 11, 2018|access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref> she was appointed by the University of Washington's [[Friends of the Educational Opportunity Program]] as a member of its [[board of trustees]],<ref name="ViewpointsUW" /><ref name="E-NewsUW" /> where she served her full three-year term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washington.edu/omad/alumni-resources/feop/|title=Friends of the Educational Opportunity Program|department=Office of Minority Affairs & Diversity|publisher=University of Washington|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022023227/http://www.washington.edu/omad/alumni-resources/feop/|archive-date=October 22, 2013|dead-url=yes|access-date=June 11, 2018}}</ref>

In the same year as her 2013 efforts in support of passing the reauthorization of the [[Violence Against Women Act]], Parker joined [[Mother Nation]],<ref name="StaffMN">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mothernation.org/staff-volunteers/|title=Staff|publisher=[[Mother Nation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611135852/https://www.mothernation.org/staff-volunteers/|archive-date=June 11, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=June 11, 2018|quote=Deborah joined the Mother Nation Team as Policy Analyst in February 2016. Prior to her new role, Deborah was an Honorary Board Member since 2013, after eight months of supporting Mother Nation through advocacy, donation of funds and house items along with clothing.}}</ref><ref name="MotherNationRC">{{Cite news|last=Robinson|first=Chetanya|date=April 19, 2017|title=Nonprofit agency helps fill the gaps in services for Native American women|url=http://realchangenews.org/2017/04/19/nonprofit-agency-helps-fill-gaps-services-native-american-women|dead-url=no|work=[[Real Change]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611140440/http://realchangenews.org/2017/04/19/nonprofit-agency-helps-fill-gaps-services-native-american-women|archive-date=June 11, 2018|access-date=June 11, 2018|quote=Deborah Parker&nbsp;[...] started volunteering with Mother Nation in 2013, the same year she successfully fought to have a provision of the Violence Against Women Act allow Native women to prosecute non-Native abusers.&nbsp;[...] Parker is now a policy analyst with Mother Nation. She said she was drawn to the organization after seeing how positively Native women responded to its culturally grounded services—that and founder Hill's dedication.}}</ref> then called Native Women in Need,<ref name="AboutMN">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mothernation.org/about/|title=About|publisher=Mother Nation|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611135852/https://www.mothernation.org/about/|archive-date=June 11, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=June 11, 2018|quote=Native Women in Need, an advocacy, cultural services and mentorship organization serving Native American women, officially changed its name to Mother Nation on March 8th, 2017, International Women's Day! Mother Nation is an non-profit Native women's organization that celebrates and inspires the success of Native American women in pursuit of healing from historical and intergenerational trauma.}}</ref> as an honorary board member after eight months of supporting the group.<ref name="StaffMN" /> She was initially drawn to the organization because of the work it did and the dedication of its founder.<ref name="MotherNationRC" /> From 2014 to 2017, Parker served as a trustee board member for the [[Smithsonian Institution]]'s [[National Museum of the American Indian]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.edu/Content/Governance/pdf/Appendix_A_04-07-2014_Actions.pdf|title=Appendix A: Actions of the April 7, 2014, Meeting of the Board of Regents|format=PDF|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=<!--None listed.-->|department=Governance|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611222013/https://www.si.edu/Content/Governance/pdf/Appendix_A_04-07-2014_Actions.pdf|archive-date=June 11, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=June 11, 2018|quote=<!--Boldfacing and bracketing in original.-->'''VOTED''' that the Board of Regents appoints LaDonna Harris, Victor Montejo, Deborah Parker, and Valerie Rowe to the Board of Trustees of the National Museum of the American Indian for three-year terms effective immediately. [2014.04.14]}}</ref> In October 2017, Parker was selected by [[Marysville School District]] to serve as its director of Equity, Diversity, and Indian Education<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wicks|first=Emily|date=October 18, 2017|title=MSD25 selects former Tulalip Tribes Board Member and Native American advocate to serve as Director of Equity, Diversity and Indian Education|url=https://www.msd25.org/article/28005|dead-url=no|department=News|location=Marysville, Washington|publisher=[[Marysville School District]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180605072347/https://www.msd25.org/article/28005|archive-date=June 5, 2018|access-date=June 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name="ParkerVCA">{{Cite news|last=Muhlstein|first=Julie|date=October 11, 2017|title=KSER-FM celebrates this year's Voice of the Community Awards|url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kser-radio-celebrates-this-years-voice-of-the-community-awards/|dead-url=no|department=Local News|work=[[The Herald (Everett)|The Daily Herald]]|publisher=Josh O'Connor|issn=2332-0079|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603182708/https://www.heraldnet.com/news/kser-radio-celebrates-this-years-voice-of-the-community-awards/|archive-date=June 3, 2018|access-date=June 3, 2018}}</ref> and continues to do so {{as of|2018|6|lc=y|post=.}}<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cornwell|first=Paige|date=June 11, 2018|orig-year=Updated; originally published June 10, 2018|title=They survived a school shooting as freshmen. Four years later, a diploma doesn't erase the pain.|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/they-survived-a-school-shooting-as-freshmen-four-years-later-a-diploma-doesnt-erase-the-pain/|dead-url=no|department=Local News|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|location=Seattle, Washington|publisher=[[Frank Blethen]]|issn=0745-9696|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720160247/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/they-survived-a-school-shooting-as-freshmen-four-years-later-a-diploma-doesnt-erase-the-pain/|archive-date=July 20, 2018|access-date=July 20, 2018|quote=On the reservation, 'we are still processing, and for some of us, it may be a lifetime of processing,' said Deborah Parker, the district's director of equity, diversity and Indian education and a former Tulalip Tribes vice chairwoman.}}</ref>

Parker lives in [[Tulalip, Washington]], where she is a mother to three children and two [[stepchild]]ren<ref name="ThereToHelp" /> and is married to documentary filmmaker Myron Dewey (who is of [[Paiute]] and [[Shoshone]] descent).<ref name="ParkerNIWRC" /><ref name="CoCprofile" /> {{As of|2018|7|post=,}} she is a board member for [[Our Revolution]]<ref name="AboutBoardOR" /><ref name="FirstBigTest" /> and the [[National Indigenous Women's Resource Center]];<ref name="ParkerNIWRC" /> the senior strategist for [[Pipestem Law]],<ref name="PipestemProfile" /><ref name="MotherNationSPI">{{Cite news|last=Burton|first=Lynsi|date=May 12, 2017|title=Mother Nation: Healing the trauma of native women|url=https://www.seattlepi.com/seattlenews/article/Mother-Earth-healing-the-trauma-of-native-women-11137029.php|dead-url=no|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|publisher=[[Hearst Seattle Media]]|issn=0745-970X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180611140235/https://www.seattlepi.com/seattlenews/article/Mother-Earth-healing-the-trauma-of-native-women-11137029.php|archive-date=June 11, 2018|access-date=June 11, 2018|quote=By the time Parker arrived home the next day, she learned the Senate had passed VAWA with native protections. The bill was stymied, however, as the House of Representatives sought to remove those provisions and the two chambers could not agree on a final bill. Parker, then a vice chairwoman at the Tulalip Tribes, flew to Washington, D.C., several times to lobby lawmakers. She stuffed tissues in her shoes to staunch her bleeding feet as she shuffled from office to office. 'I was up against some of the worst discrimination I've ever seen in my entire life,' Parker said of the opponents to the bill.&nbsp;'It's like we were subhuman and those old belief systems from the past were very real.'&nbsp;[...] Parker now volunteers as a policy analyst for Mother Nation and dedicates her time to helping tribes throughout the United States implement new VAWA laws as a senior strategist for Pipestem Law.}}</ref> a lawfirm specializing in representing Native American interests;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pipestemlaw.com/about-the-firm|title=About The Firm|publisher=Pipestem Law|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180610091723/http://www.pipestemlaw.com/about-the-firm|archive-date=June 10, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=June 10, 2018|quote=Pipestem Law is dedicated to protecting and enhancing the sovereign rights of tribal governments and improving the lives of Native people. We specialize in representation of tribal governments, tribal enterprises, and Native organizations with an emphasis on litigation in tribal, state, and federal courts.}}</ref> and the volunteer policy analyst for Mother Nation,<ref name="StaffMN" /><ref name="MotherNationRC" /><ref name="MotherNationSPI" /> a [[nonprofit organization]] supporting Native American women.<ref name="AboutMN" />

==Activism==
Parker describes her activism and resilience to resist despite hardships as "warrior status".<ref name="Lane2018" />{{rp|212|quote=<!--HTML entities to fix quote display error.-->Deborah Parker is determined to protect her Native sisters and tribal youth. Her resilience to rise up despite the hardships is what she calls &#39;warrior status,&#39; and demands we rethink what it means to be a true warrior.}} She has been the recipient of numerous awards relating to her activism and tribal outreach, including the [[Native Action Network]]'s 2010 Enduring Spirit Award,<ref name="EnduringSpiritAwardNAN" /><ref name="ThereToHelp" /> the [[National Indian Education Association]]'s 2011 Parent of the Year Award,<ref name="ViewpointsUW" /> the [[Daughters of the American Revolution]]'s 2013 Community Service Award,<ref name="CommunityExtraApplause">{{Cite news|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=June 6, 2013|title=Community Extra: Applause|url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/community-extra-applause-165/|dead-url=no|department=Local News|work=[[The Herald (Everett)|The Daily Herald]]|publisher=Josh O'Connor|issn=2332-0079|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718215246/https://www.heraldnet.com/news/community-extra-applause-165/|archive-date=July 18, 2018|access-date=July 18, 2018}}</ref> Potlatch Fund's 2013 Pearl Capoeman-Baller Civic Participation Award,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Cleary|first=Niki|date=November 6, 2013|title=Potlatch fund recognizes Native America's game changers|url=http://www.tulalipnews.com/wp/2013/11/06/potlatch-fund-recognizes-native-americas-game-changers/|dead-url=no|work=Tulalip News|location=Tulalip|publisher=Tulalip Tribes of Washington|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180605054202/http://www.tulalipnews.com/wp/2013/11/06/potlatch-fund-recognizes-native-americas-game-changers/|archive-date=June 5, 2018|access-date=June 5, 2018|via=Kim Kalliber|quote=This year, Tulalip's own Vice-Chairwoman Deborah Parker was among the recognized. She spoke about the experience in a recent interview.}}</ref> the Snohomish County Human Rights Commission's 2016 Human Rights Award,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Muhlstein|first=Julie|date=December 9, 2016|title=Everett event to honor those who bolster dignity, equality|url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/awards-to-honor-movers-and-shakers-in-human-rights/|dead-url=no|department=Local News|work=The Daily Herald|publisher=Josh O'Connor|issn=2332-0079|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603185201/https://www.heraldnet.com/news/awards-to-honor-movers-and-shakers-in-human-rights/|archive-date=June 3, 2018|access-date=June 3, 2018}}</ref> and [[KSER]]'s 2017 Voice of the Community Award for Community Impact by an Individual.<ref name="ParkerVCA" /> In September 2015, she was honored as the first of fifty in ''[[Indian Country Today]]''{{'}}s 50 Faces of Indian Country 2015.<ref name="Parker50Faces">{{Cite news|author=<!--None listed, by ICMN staff.-->|date=September 1, 2015|title=50 Faces of Indian Country: Parker, Miller, Begay, Jacobs, Valdo|url=https://indiancountrymedianetwork.com/culture/arts-entertainment/50-faces-of-indian-country-parker-miller-begay-jacobs-valdo/|dead-url=yes|department=Culture (Arts & Entertainment)|work=Indian Country Today|publisher=Indian Country Media Network|issn=1066-5501|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911100607/https://indiancountrymedianetwork.com/culture/arts-entertainment/50-faces-of-indian-country-parker-miller-begay-jacobs-valdo/|archive-date=September 11, 2017|access-date=June 5, 2018}}</ref> Parker was also the [[keynote]] speaker at the second annual Faith and Action Climate Team (FACT) Conference in October 2017.<ref name="LoveAtTheCrossroads" /><ref>{{Cite news|author-last=McDade|author-first=Georgia S.|editor-last=Green|editor-first=Marcus Harrison|editor-link=Marcus Harrison Green|date=November 8, 2018|title=Love at a Crossroads: Conference Marries Climate and Social Justice|url=https://southseattleemerald.com/2017/11/08/love-at-a-crossroads-conference-marries-climate-and-social-justice/|dead-url=no|department=Community|work=[[South Seattle Emerald]]|publisher=Marcus Harrison Green|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718200518/https://southseattleemerald.com/2017/11/08/love-at-a-crossroads-conference-marries-climate-and-social-justice/|archive-date=July 18, 2018|access-date=July 18, 2018|quote=The keynote speaker was Native American Deborah Parker of the Tulalip Tribe. Whether addressing us or answering questions she oozed calm. She said she spent most of her time 'healing, not hurting' and encouraged us to do the same. She used the word 'protect' often in her address.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eatingforahealthyplanet.org/conference-program_2017.pdf|format=PDF|title=Love at the Crossroads: Climate and Social Justice Conference|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=<!--None listed.-->|publisher=[[Mount Zion Baptist Church (Seattle, Washington)|Mount Zion Baptist Church]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718200527/https://www.eatingforahealthyplanet.org/conference-program_2017.pdf|archive-date=July 18, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=July 18, 2018|via=Eating for a Healthy Planet}}</ref>

===2012–13 Violence Against Women Act reauthorization===
[[File:Congresswoman Pelosi at the Violence Against Women Act signing (8556419967).jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.5|alt=Photograph of Barack Obama signing the VAWA reauthorization, surrounded by numerous major players, including Deborah Parker|On March 7, 2013, [[Barack Obama]] signed the reauthorization act with Deborah Parker (left, with hat) by his side.]]
During the political battle leading up to the [[Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act of 2013|2013 reauthorization]] of the [[Violence Against Women Act]] (VAWA), Parker was "vital" in the campaigning that pushed for reauthorization and her public testimony to [[United States Congress|Congress]] in particular was influential.<ref name="ProgressiveMajority" /><ref name="Lane2018" />{{rp|209|quote=Her courage in sharing her personal story of sexual violence with congress was vital in the passing of the 2013 Violence Against Women Act (VAWA). [...] Her dignified poise and presence was pivotal and necessary to pass the tribal provisions that protect Native women and their communities in the VAWA.}} While in [[Washington, D.C.]], for an April 2012 meeting with the [[Environmental Protection Agency]],<ref name="ParkerPublicStatementVAWA">{{Cite speech|last=Parker|first=Deborah|date=April 25, 2012|title=Women Senators, Tribal Leader Discuss Importance of VAWA Improvements|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yIV7-XASQy8&t=12s|access-date=June 8, 2018|type=Video|time=0:12–5:55|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[Senator Patty Murray]]|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref><ref name="RSSbyNIWRC">{{Cite magazine|author=<!--None listed.-->|editor1-last=Agtuca|editor1-first=Jacqueline|editor2-last=Cheam|editor2-first=Tang|title=Passage of More Inclusive Violence Against Women Act|url=http://www.niwrc.org/files/Restoration-V9.2.pdf|dead-url=no|format=PDF|magazine=Restoration of Sovereignty & Safety|publisher=[[National Indigenous Women's Resource Center]]|publication-date=June 2012|volume=9<!--PDF incorrectly reports "Volume XX", which WorldCat also uses, despite it being Volume 9. The cover date is also wrong by a month; it says "May", but should be "April".-->|issue=2|pages=22–25|oclc=4947882874|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180609054901/http://www.niwrc.org/files/Restoration-V9.2.pdf|archive-date=June 9, 2018|access-date=June 9, 2018}}</ref> Parker visited the staff of [[Washington (state)|Washington]] senator [[Patty Murray]] to discuss salmon and natural resource issues.<ref name="MurrayHonored">{{Cite press release|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=March 6, 2013|title=Murray Honored by NCAI for Work to Protect Tribal Women in VAWA|url=https://www.murray.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/newsreleases?ID=4e8ab2fb-02e7-4ce7-94bb-50d2583ea1c2|dead-url=no|type=Press release|department=Newsroom (News Releases)|work=[[Patty Murray|Office of United States Senator Senator Patty Murray]]|publisher=[[United States Senate]]|location=Washington, D.C.|archive-url=https://archive.is/20180617060620/https://www.murray.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/2013/3/murray-honored-by-ncai-for-work-to-protect-tribal-women-in-vawa#selection-519.0-575.274|archive-date=June 17, 2018|access-date=June 17, 2018}}</ref> During the visit, she learned about the efforts to pass the Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act of 2012 and the struggle that Murray's team were having with keeping support for a provision on tribal jurisdiction.<ref name="MurrayHonored" /><ref name="TLPISpeech">{{Cite speech|last=Parker|first=Deborah|date=December 6, 2012|title=Deborah Parker Addressing 13th National Indian Nations Conference|event=13th National Indian Nations Conference: Justice for Victims of Crime|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qE2y32ofDCk|access-date=July 21, 2018|type=Video|time=11:50–14:55|location=[[Agua Caliente Reservation]], California|publisher=[[Tribal Law and Policy Institute]]|publication-date=June 22, 2013|via=[[YouTube]]|postscript=. Title of speech: "Strength from Within: Violence Against Women Act (VAWA) and Mobilizing Tribal Government".}}</ref> According to the team, the reauthorization would likely fail, especially with the tribal provision, because the legislation "lacked a face."<ref name="StoriesOfPain" /> After being asked whether she knew any stories that could help the effort, Parker asked to speak directly with Murray.<ref name="MurrayHonored" /><ref name="TLPISpeech" /> Murray was on the [[Senate floor]] at the time; she agreed to leave immediately to meet privately with Parker.<ref name="TLPISpeech" />

Parker and Murray met later that afternoon to discuss the reauthorization bill<ref name="StoriesOfPain" /><ref name="MurrayHonored" /> and the inclusion of new provisions to allow [[tribal court]]s to prosecute non–Native Americans for crimes against women and families on tribal lands.<ref name="RSSbyNIWRC" /><ref name="TLPISpeech" /> Parker, committed to ensuring that the VAWA was reauthorized with tribal provisions, decided that "she had to set aside her fear and become 'the face' and the voice for the issue of Native women and rape."<ref name="StoriesOfPain" /> This was not something she originally planned to do.<ref name="TulalipLeaderSpeaks" /> The next day after the meeting, on April 25, she detailed in a [[press conference]] to Congress experiences both she and other women she knew had with violence and sexual abuse on reservations, describing herself as "a Native American statistic".<ref name="StoriesOfPain" /><ref name="ParkerPublicStatementVAWA" /><ref name="RSSbyNIWRC" /><ref name="MurrayHonored" /> It was the first time Parker had publicly talked about the experiences she had.<ref name="TLPISpeech" />

The [[United States Senate|Senate]] passed the VAWA reauthorization the following day<ref name="StoriesOfPain" />{{rp|232|quote=The Senate passed VAWA 68–31 the next day.}}<ref name="RSSbyNIWRC" /> with the protections for Native Americans included,<ref name="MotherNationSPI" /> though [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] in the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] initially sought to remove them.<ref name="TulalipLeaderSpeaks" /><ref name="MotherNationSPI" /> Parker began to aggressively lobby in favor of the reauthorization and sought to convince members of Congress to support both it and its tribal provisions, so much so that then-president Obama got to know her by her native name<ref name="ProsecutingAJA" /> and her "toes bled" from all the walking.<ref name="ProsecutingAJA" /><ref name="MotherNationSPI" /> She attended national cable news programs and provided interviews to newspapers across the country in support of the legislation.<ref name="MurrayHonored" /> While lobbying the opponents of the bill, Parker felt she was "up against some of the worst discrimination I've ever seen in my entire life" and that Native American women were treated "like we were subhuman".<ref name="MotherNationSPI" /> The House of Representatives began proposing weaker language to the Senate in an attempt at compromise on the provision; Murray, Parker, and the rest refused.<ref name="MurrayHonored" /> Before long, the opposition to the reauthorization and its tribal provisions eroded in the House and strong [[bipartisan support]] emerged.<ref name="MurrayHonored" />

By the time the final bill was signed into law in March 2013, it included the tribal law provisions that Parker promoted.<ref name="ProudDay" /><ref name="RayOfHope" /><ref name="ProsecutingAJA" /> Four months later, in July 2013, Parker was honored by the [[Obama White House]] as one of the Open Government and Civic Hacking [[Champions of Change]] "working to improve their communities through technology, innovation, and civic participation."<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Forde|first1=Brian|author-link=Brian Forde|last2=Gilman|first2=Hollie Russon|date=July 29, 2013|title=Honoring Open Government and Civic Hacking Champions of Change|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/blog/2013/07/29/honoring-open-government-and-civic-hacking-champions-change|dead-url=no|department=Blog|work=The White House of President Barack Obama|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603065617/https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/blog/2013/07/29/honoring-open-government-and-civic-hacking-champions-change|archive-date=June 3, 2018|access-date=June 3, 2018|via=[[National Archives and Records Administration]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Montreuil|first=Brandi N.|date=August 6, 2013|title=Deborah Parker honored as a White House Open Government Champion of Change|url=http://www.tulalipnews.com/wp/2013/08/06/deborah-parker-honored-as-a-white-house-open-government-champion-of-change/|dead-url=no|department=Local News|work=Tulalip News|publisher=[[Tulalip Tribes of Washington]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603070128/http://www.tulalipnews.com/wp/2013/08/06/deborah-parker-honored-as-a-white-house-open-government-champion-of-change/|archive-date=June 3, 2018|access-date=June 3, 2018}}</ref> For Murray, the VAWA reauthorization "would have never happened if Parker had not gone public with her story on [[Capitol Hill]]" and she "made the absolute difference at the absolute critical time" by "making her personal story become the face of what this was about".<ref name="CampaignAd">{{Cite news|last=Hotakainen|first=Rob|date=October 13, 2016|title=Campaign ad features Washington state woman who disclosed sexual and physical abuse|url=https://www.sanluisobispo.com/news/politics-government/article107944232.html|dead-url=no|department=Politics & Government|work=[[San Luis Obispo Tribune]]|location=Washington|publisher=Ken Riddick|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722052746/https://www.sanluisobispo.com/news/politics-government/article107944232.html|archive-date=July 22, 2018|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> Around the same time, playwright [[Mary Kathryn Nagle]] released ''[[Sliver of a Full Moon]]'', a play about the events surrounding the VAWA reauthorization that tells the stories of five Native American women and two Native men.<ref name="SliverOfAFullMoon">{{Cite press release|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=September 19, 2014|title=Sliver of a Full Moon to be staged for world leaders|url=https://www.nativetimes.com/index.php/culture/art-23/10511-sliver-of-a-full-moon-to-be-staged-for-world-leaders|dead-url=no|type=Press release|work=[[Native American Times]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720152652/https://www.nativetimes.com/index.php/culture/art-23/10511-sliver-of-a-full-moon-to-be-staged-for-world-leaders|archive-date=July 20, 2018|access-date=July 20, 2018|quote=Professional actors will join them to portray Congressman Tom Cole, Eastern Band Cherokee Councilwoman Terri Henry, and Tulalip Tribe's Vice-Chairwoman Deborah Parker.}}</ref> Among the five women is Deborah Parker, played by Jennifer Bobiwash.<ref name="SliverOfAFullMoon" />

Later, in October 2015, the tribal provisions were officially implemented for all tribes after a "very successful" pilot program involving the [[Tulalip]], [[Pascua Yaqui]], and [[Umatilla people|Umatilla]] tribes.<ref name="ProsecutingAJA" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=McConnell|first=Charles|date=October 6, 2015|title=Tribes: Domestic violence program 'very successful,' but challenges remain|url=https://cronkitenews.azpbs.org/2015/10/06/tribes-domestic-violence-program-very-successful-but-challenges-remain/|dead-url=no|department=Legal|work=[[Cronkite News]]|publisher=[[Arizona PBS]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722052343/https://cronkitenews.azpbs.org/2015/10/06/tribes-domestic-violence-program-very-successful-but-challenges-remain/|archive-date=July 22, 2018|access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> A year afterward, in October 2016, Parker was featured in the second [[campaign advertisement]] of Patty Murray's re-election in the [[2016 United States Senate election in Washington]].<ref name="CampaignAd" /> In the video, Parker briefly recounted her experiences with sexual assault and her work with Murray to help pass the VAWA reauthorization.<ref name="CampaignAd" />

===2016 US presidential election===
During the [[2016 Democratic National Convention]], Parker served as one of the platform committee members representing [[Bernie Sanders]]<ref name="ParkerDNPC" /><ref name="ProgressiveMajority" /> after having been an early and vocal supporter of [[Bernie Sanders presidential campaign, 2016|his 2016 presidential campaign]].<ref name="ParkerDNPC" /><ref name="ParkerInterviewTYT" /> She was initially hesitant to do so, but accepted then–[[Democratic National Committee]] chairwoman [[Debbie Wasserman Schultz]]'s offer to join the platform committee, seeing it as an opportunity to advance the causes she supported, particularly "[[Native American sovereignty]], [[climate justice]], to increase&nbsp;[...] protections for women, [and] [[income inequality]]";<ref name="ParkerInterviewTYT" /> and to {{"'}}honor' Sanders and 'represent his vision' on the committee."<ref>{{Cite news|last=Parks|first=Maryalice|date=June 10, 2016|title=Bernie Sanders Goes Home to Contemplate What's Next|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/bernie-sanders-home-contemplate/story?id=39762964|dead-url=no|department=Politics|work=[[ABC News]]|location=Burlington, Vermont|publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614044708/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/bernie-sanders-home-contemplate/story?id=39762964|archive-date=June 14, 2018|access-date=June 14, 2018|quote=Deborah Parker, a Native-American tribal leader and one of Sanders' picks to the platform committee, said Thursday during the senator's rally in Washington, D.C., that she hoped to 'honor' Sanders and 'represent his vision' on the committee.}}</ref> As a platform committee member, Parker "helped to ensure that Native policy initiatives were ultimately rolled into the party's larger platform."<ref name="SearchForAnswers" /> She also authored one of the twelve "priority amendments" to the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] platform that the Sanders campaign supported, which sought to introduce language that explicitly promoted using [[global warming]] as a "test" for whether any policy or decision should be supported within relevant federal agencies.<ref>{{Cite press release|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=July 7, 2016|title=Sanders Campaigns Priority Amendments to Democratic Platform|url=https://berniesanders.com/sanders-campaigns-priority-amendments-democratic-platform/|dead-url=no|type=Press release|work=Friends of Bernie Sanders|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614054112/https://berniesanders.com/sanders-campaigns-priority-amendments-democratic-platform/|archive-date=June 14, 2018|access-date=June 14, 2018|quote=<!--Boldfacing and capitalization in original.-->'''10. KEYSTONE PIPELINE AMENDMENT – By Deborah Parker'''[:] On Page 19, Line 26, after 'We support President Obama's decision to reject the Keystone XL pipeline' add: ', and we support the test he used to arrive at that decision: whether or not a policy would "significantly exacerbate" global warming. A similar test should be applied across all relevant federal agencies and decisions.[']}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=August 25, 2016|title=Sen. Bernie Sanders joins opposition to Dakota Access Pipeline|url=https://www.indianz.com/News/2016/08/25/sen-bernie-sanders-joins-opposition-to-d.asp|dead-url=no|department=News|work=Indianz|publisher=[[Ho-Chunk Inc.]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614070132/https://www.indianz.com/News/2016/08/25/sen-bernie-sanders-joins-opposition-to-d.asp|archive-date=June 14, 2018|access-date=June 14, 2018|quote=While Sanders did not win the Democratic nomination for president, his tribal allies secured a provision in the party platform that calls on the federal government to ensure that its actions do not contribute to climate change. The language was proposed by Deborah Parker, the former vice chair of the Tulalip Tribes in Washington.}}</ref>

In June 2016, on the first day of the platform drafting hearing in [[St. Louis]], Parker proposed a substitution amendment that replaced and strengthened the language in the section on honoring tribal nations.<ref name="Day1DNC">{{Cite video|last=Parker|first=Deborah|date=June 24, 2016|title=Democratic Platform Drafting Hearing – St. Louis – Day 1 PM section|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R713OylyhIg&t=8h2m26s|access-date=June 16, 2018|type=Video|time=8:01:55–8:12:39|location=St. Louis|publisher=[[Democratic National Convention]]|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> [[Elijah Cummings]], the chairman presiding over the hearing, allotted Parker additional time and gave her the floor.<ref name="Day1DNC" /><ref name="HereBeforeUs">{{Cite news|last=Abdelaziz|first=Laila|date=July 10, 2016|title=To those who were here before us|url=http://mondoweiss.net/2016/07/those-here-before/|dead-url=no|work=[[Mondoweiss]]|publisher=Center for Economic Research and Social Change|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616103939/http://mondoweiss.net/2016/07/those-here-before/|archive-date=June 16, 2018|access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref> While reading the amendment text, she was overwhelmed by the moment and began to cry.<ref name="Day1DNC" /><ref name="HereBeforeUs" /> After some silence, [[James Zogby]] continued where Parker left off until she regained her composure and resumed.<ref name="Day1DNC" /><ref name="HereBeforeUs" /> [[Barbara Lee]] noted afterward that in all her decades of attending [[Democratic National Convention]]s, she did not recall "any provision or plank in our platform that acknowledges the first people of the United States".<ref name="Day1DNC" /> [[Cornel West]] likewise commented that Parker's "very existence&nbsp;[...] on this committee is historically unprecedented".<ref name="Day1DNC" /> After further commendations from other committee members, and Cummings' recognition of Parker's "passion", the proposal was passed unanimously to a standing ovation.<ref name="Day1DNC" /><ref name="HereBeforeUs" />

Specifically, the amendment text committed the Democratic Party to "uphold, honor, and strengthen to the highest extent possible the United States' fundamental trust and responsibility, grounded in the Constitution and treaties, to American Indian and [[Alaska Native]] tribes" because "throughout our history we have failed to live up to that trust".<ref name="Day1DNC" /> It also committed the party to restoring tribal lands to indigenous tribes; increasing funding and support for tribal communities, particularly in infrastructure, education, and health care; eliminating school and sports mascots that are derogatory, stereotyping, or racist toward Native Americans; and improving both tribal jurisdiction and indigenous voting rights.<ref name="Day1DNC" /> Lastly, the amendment endorsed "environmental justice in Indian Country" and acknowledged "the past injustices and the misguided, harmful federal and state policies and actions based on outdated and discredited values and beliefs that resulted in the destruction of the Indian nations' economies, social, and religious systems, the taking of their lands, and the creation of intergenerational trauma that exists to this day."<ref name="Day1DNC" /> The amendment text was fully retained in the July 1 draft version<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://demconvention.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/2016-DEMOCRATIC-PARTY-PLATFORM-DRAFT-7.1.16.pdf|title=2016 Democratic Party Platform – DRAFT – July 1, 2016|format=PDF|date=July 1, 2016|department=Democratic Platform Committee|website=[[2016 Democratic National Convention]]|publisher=[[Democratic National Committee]]|pages=14–16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111191440/https://demconvention.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/2016-DEMOCRATIC-PARTY-PLATFORM-DRAFT-7.1.16.pdf|archive-date=November 11, 2016|dead-url=yes|access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref> and further expanded to strengthen language for [[Native Hawaiians]] by the time the official platform was released on July 21.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.demconvention.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Democratic-Party-Platform-7.21.16-no-lines.pdf|title=2016 Democratic Party Platform – July 21, 2016|format=PDF|date=July 21, 2016|department=Democratic Platform Committee|website=2016 Democratic National Convention|publisher=Democratic National Committee|pages=21–23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204034439/https://www.demconvention.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Democratic-Party-Platform-7.21.16-no-lines.pdf|archive-date=December 4, 2016|dead-url=yes|access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref>

Shortly after [[Our Revolution]] formed in August 2016,<ref name="ReturningToRoots">{{Cite news|last=Guttenplan|first=Don David|author-link=D. D. Guttenplan|date=August 25, 2016|title=Returning to His Roots, Sanders Launches 'Our Revolution'|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/returning-to-his-roots-sanders-launches-our-revolution/|dead-url=no|department=Election 2016|work=[[The Nation]]|publisher=[[Katrina vanden Heuvel]]|issn=0027-8378|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614062748/https://www.thenation.com/article/returning-to-his-roots-sanders-launches-our-revolution/|archive-date=June 14, 2018|access-date=June 14, 2018|quote=But, as Sanders reminded his supporters last night during the national launch of Our Revolution, the new organization founded to carry forward the work of his 'political revolution,' by every other measure they succeeded far beyond what anyone (including the candidate himself) would have deemed possible even a year ago.}}</ref> Parker joined it as a member of its board of directors.<ref name="FirstBigTest" /><ref>{{Cite press release|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=<!--None listed.-->|title=Our Revolution Announces Formation of Board|url=https://ourrevolution.com/press/our-revolution-announces-formation-of-board/|dead-url=no|type=Press release|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[Our Revolution]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614062733/https://ourrevolution.com/press/our-revolution-announces-formation-of-board/|archive-date=June 14, 2018|access-date=June 13, 2018}}</ref>

===Protests===
Throughout the years, Parker has opposed and protested multiple pipeline projects out of concern for their environmental impact and effects on tribal lands. In September 2016, Parker and other [[Tulalip]] tribal members joined [[Standing Rock]] in [[Dakota Access Pipeline protests|protesting]] the [[Dakota Access Pipeline]].<ref name="FirstBigTest" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Winters|first=Chris|date=September 16, 2016|title=Tulalips support Standing Rock Sioux protesting oil pipeline|url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/tulalips-support-standing-rock-sioux-protesting-oil-pipeline/|dead-url=no|department=Local News|work=[[The Herald (Everett)|The Daily Herald]]|location=Tulalip|publisher=Josh O'Connor|issn=2332-0079|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603081843/https://www.heraldnet.com/news/tulalips-support-standing-rock-sioux-protesting-oil-pipeline/|archive-date=June 3, 2018|access-date=June 3, 2018|quote=On Friday, about 100 Tulalip members took part in a rally and march in downtown Seattle, said Deborah Parker, a former Tulalip board member who went down with her family.}}</ref> A month later, on November 15, 2016, Parker joined [[Eryn Wise]], [[LaDonna Brave Bull Allard]], and [[Judith LeBlanc]] for [[Dakota Access Pipeline protests#"National Day of Action"|the protests' "National Day of Action"]], during which the four staged a sit-in at the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|Army Corps of Engineers]] headquarters and led a crowd of approximately 1,000 protestors around [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{Cite news|author=<!--None listed.-->|date=November 16, 2016|title=Native women lead massive march to White House to stop Dakota Access Pipeline|url=https://www.indianz.com/News/2016/11/16/native-women-lead-massive-march-to-stop.asp|dead-url=no|department=News|work=Indianz|publisher=[[Ho-Chunk Inc.]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603093221/https://www.indianz.com/News/2016/11/16/native-women-lead-massive-march-to-stop.asp|archive-date=June 3, 2018|access-date=June 3, 2018|quote=[Eryn] Wise, who is from the Jicarilla Apache Nation and Laguna Pueblo, was joined by three other Native women leaders—LaDonna Brave Bull Allard (Standing Rock Sioux Tribe), Deborah Parker (Tulalip Tribes) and Judith LeBlanc (Caddo Nation)—for the #NoDAPL Day of Action. After staging a sit-in at the headquarters of the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, they led the crowd of about 1,000 people down the streets of Washington, even passing by the newly opened Trump Hotel on Pennsylvania Avenue NW.}}</ref>

Parker joined other indigenous leaders and groups in January 2017 for the [[2017 Women's March]] and marched in the [[Women's March on Washington]].<ref name="SeattleTimes2018">{{Cite news|last=Cornwell|first=Paige|date=January 20, 2018|title=Seattle's Women's March: How it unfolded|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/womens-march-today-2018-womxn-act-on-seattle/|dead-url=no|department=Seattle News|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|publisher=[[Frank Blethen]]|issn=0745-9696|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617010231/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/womens-march-today-2018-womxn-act-on-seattle/|archive-date=June 17, 2018|access-date=June 16, 2018|quote=<!--Boldfacing in original.-->'''Update, 10:55 a.m.:'''&nbsp;[...] Former Tulalip Tribes vice chair Deborah Parker recounted marching in Washington D.C. last year but said 'it's good to be home' this year. 'Last year I had the time of my life in D.C. because there was so much love,' she said. 'Millions of women and supporters all came together and it was the most peaceful march and one of the most peaceful times to stand united.'&nbsp;}}</ref> During the protest, a new group was formed called [[Indigenous Women Rise]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=Curry|first=Colleen|date=March 10, 2017|title=Native Girls Rise|url=https://www.globalcitizen.org/en/content/native-girls-rise/|dead-url=no|department=Girls & Women|work=[[Global Citizen (website)|Global Citizen]]|publisher=[[Global Poverty Project]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617005945/https://www.globalcitizen.org/en/content/native-girls-rise/|archive-date=June 17, 2018|access-date=June 16, 2018|quote=Just this January, at the Women's March on Washington, a loosely organized coalition called Indigenous Women Rise popped up as an umbrella group for activists who have, until now, been working separately on a variety of issues important to Native communities: voting rights, job opportunities, environmental concerns, ending violence against women. Together under one banner, the women are launching a movement that seems to be gaining momentum.}}</ref> of which she became a co-founder.<ref name="CofounderIWR" /><ref name="IG2017TC" /> A year later, in January 2018, she participated in the [[2018 Women's March]] in Seattle, where she recounted the previous year's events.<ref name="SeattleTimes2018" />

In an April 2018 article, Parker criticized Canadian prime minister [[Justin Trudeau]] and advocated for opposition to the [[Trans Mountain Pipeline]] in solidarity with [[First Nations]] peoples.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Parker|first=Deborah|date=April 20, 2018|title=Stop this pipeline|url=https://countercurrents.org/2018/04/20/stop-this-pipeline/|dead-url=no|department=Environmental Protection|work=Countercurrents|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614065851/https://countercurrents.org/2018/04/20/stop-this-pipeline/|archive-date=June 14, 2018|access-date=June 14, 2018}}</ref> Our Revolution released a statement doing likewise on the same day.<ref>{{Cite press release|last=May|first=Diane|date=April 20, 2018|title=Our Revolution Calls on Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau to Stop Trans Mountain Pipeline|url=https://www.einpresswire.com/article/443167854/our-revolution-calls-on-canadian-prime-minister-justin-trudeau-to-stop-trans-mountain-pipeline|dead-url=no|type=Press release|work=EIN Presswire|publisher=IPD Group|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616063913/https://www.einpresswire.com/article/443167854/our-revolution-calls-on-canadian-prime-minister-justin-trudeau-to-stop-trans-mountain-pipeline|archive-date=June 16, 2018|access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref>

==Views==
During a 2016 interview, Parker described a national restriction on gun possession for those previously charged with [[domestic violence]] as a "necessity" for protecting women.<ref name="ParkerInterviewTYT" /> She also censured [[Donald Trump]]'s [[List of nicknames used by Donald Trump|usage]] of "[[Pocahontas]]" as a nickname for [[Elizabeth Warren]] (who claims [[Cherokee]] and [[Lenape|Delaware]] heritage), which she described as "very insulting"; and Trump's past treatment of [[tribal nation]]s and [[Tribal sovereignty in the United States|their sovereignty]] more generally.<ref name="ParkerInterviewTYT" />

Parker is critical of the US government's current and historic treatment of indigenous populations, comparing [[Native American reservation]]s to "[[concentration camp]]s".<ref name="Lane2018" />{{rp|211|quote=<!--HTML entities to fix quote display error.-->&nbsp;&#39;Politics aside, the government has kept us [Natives] away on our reservations in these places that are much like concentration camps for many,&#39; she switches between realities fluidly, &#39;we [Americans] don&#39;t know that because we haven&#39;t identified it as such.&#39; She repositions herself again, &#39;we&#39;ve just been told to be happy on the land we have but truly the government put us on these concentration camps. And yeah, it&#39;s a part of our traditional lands,&#39; she recognizes, &#39;but in the mind of the government, "that&#39;s your reservation, stay there!"&nbsp;&#39;&nbsp;}}

Regarding the [[traditional knowledge]] of indigenous peoples, especially [[traditional ecological knowledge]] and [[traditional medicine]], Parker supports rules and guidelines which preserve indigenous ways of life and respect the privacy of certain traditions and practices.<ref name="TraditionalKnowledge">{{Cite web|url=https://www7.nau.edu/itep/main/tcc/Tribes/tdk_sguard|title=Traditional Knowledge: Safeguarding Indigenous Knowledge|last=Wall|first=Dennis|date=December 2013<!--According to attached PDF; no publication day.-->|department=Tribes & Climate Change (Tribal Climate Change Profile)|website=[[Northern Arizona University]]|publisher=[[Institute for Tribal Environmental Professionals]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721181459/https://www7.nau.edu/itep/main/tcc/Tribes/tdk_sguard|archive-date=July 21, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=July 21, 2018}}</ref> She also emphasizes the importance of viewing indigenous knowledge from an indigenous perspective, which may differ from "the Western-science approach" to these issues.<ref name="TraditionalKnowledge" />

