'''Richard E. Pattis''' is a [[senior lecturer]] at the [[University of California, Irvine]]'s [[Donald Bren School of Information and Computer Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ics.uci.edu/faculty/profiles/view_faculty.php?ucinetid=pattis|title=Faculty profile: Richard E Pattis}}</ref>

He is the author of the [[Karel (programming language)|Karel programming language]], and published ''Karel the Robot: A gentle introduction to the art of programming''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mace|first=Scott|title=Cybertronics releases low-cost logo for Apple II|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CDAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA27|accessdate=17 December 2010|newspaper=[[Infoworld]]|date=6 September 1982}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Michael Nicita, Ronald Petrusha|first=Michael|title=The reader's guide to microcomputer books|year=1984|publisher=Golden-Lee|page=151|author2=Ronald Petrusha }}</ref>

Pattis has been a professor of computer science at [[Carnegie Mellon University]] and the [[University of Washington]]. He holds a [[master's degree]] from [[Stanford University]].

